    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">Office of <persName>Davis, Peixotto &amp; Co.</persName></p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Nos. 3 &amp; 5 Water Street</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Corner of Superior Street</placeName>.</p>
            <p><persName>Geo. A. Davis</persName>.</p>
            <p><placeName>NEW YORK</placeName>.</p>
            <p><persName role="author">B. F. Peixotto</persName>.</p>
            <p><placeName>CLEVELAND</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cleveland</placeName>, <date>Nov 15th 1865</date>.</p>
            <p>My dear &amp; Rev Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Thanks for your letter<lb/> of the <date>13th</date> and the earnest
                spirit you<lb/> exhibit in behalf of <placeName>Israel</placeName> and the<lb/>
                Order. No earthly triangle can<lb/> equal the joy Heaven and the life<lb/> immortal
                beyond the tomb will give<lb/> you. Your richest reward will come<lb/> alas! like
                that of every great benefac<lb/>-tor after “life's fitful fever is over.”<lb/> When
                the spirit has departed to<lb/> “the <del>it</del> undiscovered country from<lb/>
                whose frame<add>?</add> no traveller returns.”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Would to God all men entered<lb/> into the spirit of your labors,
                ap-<lb/>-preciated and valued them as<lb/> I do. Would it were that my<lb/> worldly
                means were such as<lb/> to field you that support<lb/> which wd give you the
                “ample</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>margin” for the realization of all your<lb/> aspirations in behalf of
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName>—in<lb/> the name and for the sake of
                    <placeName>Israel's</placeName><lb/> God. Be of cheerful heart dear<lb/> Friend,
                The future will be just to you<lb/> even if the present be ungrateful<lb/> and
                indifferent. “The labor we<lb/> delight in physics pain” else would<lb/> we
                    of<del>f</del>t throw aside those things<lb/> which in their personal
                relation<lb/> to us are rather “ills” than<lb/> “benefits.” We must bear the
                “whips<lb/> and scorns of time” the “proud man's<lb/>
                <sic>continuely</sic>” the “insolence of office”<lb/> and “the spurns that
                patient<lb/> merit of the unworthy taker-”<lb/> and nobly breast the tide of<lb/>
                outrageous fortune—the seas<lb/> of trouble that ever and<lb/> none beat against
                our<lb/> rock bound—(heart felt)<lb/> ribs—(brain and soul)</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">To be disheartened—to give way<lb/> is to field up the “good fight”
                and</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>“perish quickly, <add>?</add>!” To <hi rend="underline">me</hi> should these<lb/>
                consoling words be uttered rather<lb/> than to <hi rend="underline">you</hi>. For
                have you not withstood<lb/> all these throes of time and fate?<lb/> Have you not
                tasted the bitter cup<lb/> and yet survived its draught, to live<lb/> a life more
                blessed? Heaven hath<lb/> been with you still, and your heart is<lb/> yet ambient in
                its effulgent love for<lb/> the noble cause espoused five and<lb/> twenty years ago.
                And though it<lb/> be as <persName>Byron</persName> hath it—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">“Years still fire from the brain<lb/> As vigor from the limb<lb/>
                And life's enchanted cup<lb/> But sparkles near the brim”<lb/> Yet to age there
                comes no “chilling<lb/> frost” if the heart be warm and<lb/> the spirit steadfast.
                There is “a<lb/> green youth in age” that makes of<lb/> it a holy and a blessed
                time.<lb/> Please Heaven such be thine for<lb/> eye! Xxx I have sent the recp<lb/>
                to <persName>Miss L &amp; W</persName>. I will take the</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>copy of the Pentateuch @ $25 the<lb/> price you name. I will try to dispose<lb/> of
                the other books now that I know<lb/> their value.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have sent (<date>Sunday</date>)<lb/> a list of the Lodges that
                up<lb/> to that time had reported<lb/> (I had not yours of the <date>13th</date>
                then)<lb/> to <placeName>N. Y.</placeName> for publication. You<lb/> will see them
                mentioned in<lb/> the “Messenger” and if it<lb/> so please you add to the<lb/> list
                those you have given<lb/> me (except Har Nevoh) which<lb/> I noticed in the <hi
                    rend="underline">Occident</hi> as<lb/> having acted and publish<lb/> in the best
                of Jewish Periodicals<lb/> your own paper. I will<lb/> be gratified, or if you prefer<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">wait</hi> till all returns are<lb/> in and then let me<lb/>
                have 2 or 3 pages to<lb/> write up &amp; I will</p>
            <p>In haste</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With Sincerest wishes</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">for your health &amp; happiness</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">your Friend &amp; Bro</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">B. F. Peixotto</persName>
            </p>
            <p><addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee>. <placeName>Phila.</placeName></p>
        </body>
